Vol / Page: 36
Edition:
Quote: The shingle-slips ... are also not without an interesting vegetation .<i>Ibid.</i> ..  174 In examining these angular fragments (usually called shingle in New Zealand, whence the expression `shingle slips' for these huge taluses of debris covering the mountain sides), we find that they have a polyhedrical shape, their planes being sharply defined, and cutting, as seen in the conglomerates, clean through even the hardest pebbles of which the latter are composed.
